These Wales internationals have been out of action since suffering shoulder injuries at the World Cup, but at least one is expected to be fit for the critical European Challenge Cup matches at home against Castres on January 15. Dragons boss Jones further commented that "they are impactful players who can bring a distinct quality." He added, "There's a strong possibility one of them will be back [to face Castres], though I'm uncertain which one." Jones praised the medical team, noting, "They've made excellent progress, and the medical department deserves credit for their rapid recovery efforts. They have recovered very well, and we anticipate both will participate in the European competition soon."

The Official Charts Company has confirmed a historic first: an artist simultaneously claimed the top two spots on the charts with newly released tracks. The singer expressed immense satisfaction with this achievement, stating how significant both songs were to him, making their joint ascent to the top particularly remarkable.

Sheeran's return followed a year-long hiatus from social media, dedicated to composing his third album, titled 'Divide.' This period clearly fueled fan anticipation, as the artist subsequently shattered multiple streaming records within a single week. His upbeat pop track, "Shape Of You," proved the more popular, accumulating 13.4 million streams and significantly surpassing Drake's previous record of 8.9 million for "One Dance" last summer. "Castle On The Hill," characterized by its U2-esque guitar riff, also outdid Drake's achievement with 11.07 million streams. Furthermore, on Spotify, Sheeran surpassed One Direction's global streaming record, which was set in August 2015 when "Drag Me Down" garnered 4.76 million streams in a day. "Shape Of You" itself achieved 6.13 million streams on its release Friday, escalating to 7.24 million by Monday.

This exceptional chart dominance by his singles brought an end to Clean Bandit's nine-week reign at number one. Their track, "Rockabye," fell to fourth place, while Rag 'N' Bone Man's "Human" secured the third spot. Other new entries included Sean Paul and Dua Lipa's "No Lie" at 28, and Snakehips' "Don't Leave," featuring Danish artist MØ, at 33. On the album chart, Little Mix's "Glory Days" maintained its number one position for a fifth consecutive week, making it the most successful album by a girl band since the Spice Girls' 'Spice' held the top spot for 15 weeks in 1996. Elsewhere, David Bowie's "Blackstar" re-entered the top 40 exactly a year following his passing, and his "Legacy" compilation impressively climbed from 18 to number five.

Chris Millar remains sidelined, while Keith Watson and Ally Gilchrist are still not cleared for a return. Ross County defender Paul Quinn will be rested for a week to recover from a knock sustained during the Rangers match. Positively, Michael Gardyne and Martin Woods are back in the squad after sitting out the draw with the Ibrox side, and Erik Cikos has recuperated from a dead leg.

St Johnstone's Ricky Foster expressed his satisfaction with their earlier season win at the venue and hopes for a similar result. He noted the strong desire to perform well against former teams, seeing it as an opportunity to prove oneself and emerge victorious. Foster added that these matches are enjoyable, provided they end in a win.

Ross County's Alex Schalk emphasized Saturday's game as a crucial chance to narrow the points gap with St Johnstone, urging his team to seize such opportunities. He confidently predicted an upcoming run of positive results that would propel them back into the top six, a goal the manager has for them as an established top-tier side. Despite their poor start, Schalk believes the squad's ability warrants them being alongside St Johnstone.

Previously unreleased archive footage brings together a vibrant tapestry of Ulster's past, showcasing events from Winston Churchill's notable Belfast visit in 1912 and a 1963 Viking re-enactment in a County Down coastal town, alongside stories of tourism, industrial legacy, and athletic endeavors. As part of a significant historical initiative called 'From Britain On Film', the British Film Institute (BFI) has made hundreds of previously unreleased films from its archives available for public online viewing at no cost. The collection chronicles royal tours and civic parades, including Churchill's 1912 speech at Belfast's Celtic Park, where he spoke to nationalists and endorsed Home Rule. Additionally, numerous travel films are featured, originally designed to promote Northern Ireland as a tourist destination to audiences in Great Britain and the United States, thereby boosting visitor numbers prior to the onset of the Troubles. The archive also highlights sporting events, such as the 1930 Ulster Tourist Trophy race, held at the Ards circuit in County Down, an event that drew thousands of onlookers and captivated the international motorsport community.

However, the most compelling material lies in the footage depicting everyday individuals engaged in remarkable activities. Scenes of workers in spinning mills and the construction of the M1 motorway at Stockman's Lane in Belfast showcase Northern Ireland's industrial peak. One film documents Northern Ireland's inaugural hosting of the World Ploughing Championships, where, appropriately, a local competitor claimed victory. This 1959 competition in Armoy, County Antrim, is preserved in colour footage, capturing Lawrence McMillan's triumphant moment as he secured the Golden Plough.

Yet, a 1938 recording from Belfast's Royal Victoria Hospital proves arguably the most insightful. It offers an uncommon look into its casualty department and operating theatres as they operated a decade before the National Health Service was established. While medical practices have progressed significantly over the subsequent eighty years, certain aspects of healthcare in Northern Ireland seem to persist; the film concludes with the hospital's management board chairman appealing for reduced waiting lists.

Francis Jones of Northern Ireland Screen, responsible for collecting much of this material, stated that the project's goal was to safeguard fragile films that were at risk of deterioration or loss. He added that film possesses a unique nostalgic value, distinct from engaging with textbooks or history books. "Witnessing the footage firsthand offers a visceral connection that truly resonates with viewers," he commented. The entire 'From Britain On Film' archive is accessible via the BFI Player.

North Ronaldsay Primary School's sole classroom will be held in reserve starting in August, following 12-year-old Teigan Scott's transition to secondary education in Kirkwall. This most northerly Orkney island is home to only around 50 residents. Orkney Islands Council stated the school would resume operation if additional families with young children relocate to the island. The facility also serves as a hub for local community groups. Island inhabitants attribute the scarcity of young families to inadequate transport connections. Teigan expressed to the BBC her excitement for secondary school but conveyed apprehension regarding her former school's future. "I'm eager to attend the larger school," she remarked. "However, a slight sadness lingers because the school's closure makes me fear the island could decline."

Councillor Kevin Woodbridge noted that North Ronaldsay's population has halved since his arrival in 1977. He commented, "It's deeply saddening, yet it illustrates the island's decline that has culminated in this situation." "When I first came, there were 17 pupils at the school and 127 residents on the island; now, the population stands at 50 to 60." He added, "The standard of living on the island could be significantly enhanced."

Billy Muir, who chairs the community council, described losing the school's sole pupil as "a severe setback for the community that will undoubtedly trigger wider consequences." He stated, "We require new housing to be constructed and new families to move in. A school needs several children, not just one." "Faster broadband is also essential." "There's no sense in sugar-coating things; we must be pragmatic. Hopefully, this situation draws attention to our predicament."

A spokesperson for the local authority explained: "The single classroom at North Ronaldsay Primary School is located within a building that accommodates various community amenities. The classroom will remain on standby from August and would be reactivated for educational use should families with primary-aged children relocate to the island. Meanwhile, it will stay accessible to all North Ronaldsay residents for various learning activities, overseen by the local community association. This strategy for keeping the room actively utilized was developed through discussions between Orkney Islands Council and several North Ronaldsay community groups."

Most of My Local's stores, specifically 93 out of 125, are set to close. The remaining outlets will stay open while KPMG, the appointed administrator, seeks potential buyers. Should these efforts fail, those stores too will cease operations. The company had a workforce of 1,658 individuals.

Morrisons, a supermarket chain, sold My Local to Greybull Capital last year and has since committed to offering positions to former My Local employees. The retailer found it difficult to compete in the fiercely competitive and price-war-ridden grocery market.

Formerly known as Morrisons' M Local, My Local was acquired by Greybull for £25 million. This acquisition was spearheaded by Mike Greene, an experienced figure in retail who gained public recognition from his appearance on Channel 4's The Secret Millionaire.

My Local had indicated earlier this month that administrators were alerted to assume control of the business. Just last week, Morrisons extended a helping hand to My Local's staff, proposing job opportunities within its own supermarkets in the event of store closures.

Mike Greene expressed his regret, stating that the past nine months constituted "one of the toughest retail trading periods" he had ever encountered, with My Local confronting "intense competition." He added that the management team was "unable to return the business to profitability," for which he was "truly sorry."

Mark Orton, a partner at KPMG and joint administrator, commented that the management faced "tough trading conditions," and despite their "best efforts to improve performance," My Local ultimately "was unable to return to viability." He confirmed that while most stores have now ceased operations, KPMG is engaged in "active discussions with a number of interested parties" regarding both the 32 remaining operational premises and a select few that have already shut down.

My Local's collapse highlights a challenging period for the retail industry, coming after the bankruptcies of BHS and Austin Reed. Furthermore, on Tuesday, the owners of Store Twenty One, a fashion retailer, announced plans for a restructuring that could lead to store closures and job cuts.

Lord Advocate Frank Mulholland informed Scottish Parliament members that a fatal accident inquiry would be convened regarding the death of Sheku Bayoh. Mr. Bayoh, 31, died on May 3 in police custody following an incident in Kirkcaldy. His family expressed welcome for the announcement, hoping the Lord Advocate would indeed establish the complete truth of what transpired.

Mr. Mulholland also conveyed to MSPs that additional work was still necessary from the Police Investigations and Review Commissioner (Pirc), particularly concerning the cause of death, before the overall inquiry could be finalized. He remarked on the profound impact of this tragedy on the family, having met them twice, noting their remarkable dignity in coping with their loss. He asserted they were justified in demanding answers, and that a thorough, impartial, and objective investigation was their due. Mulholland expressed confidence that this process could be conducted swiftly without compromising its comprehensiveness.

He further clarified that a fatal accident inquiry would proceed irrespective of any decisions regarding criminal proceedings, specifically because Mr. Bayoh had died while in detention. Mulholland explained that such an inquiry would permit all relevant evidence to be presented in a public court, open to both the public and media. This evidence would be rigorously scrutinized by all involved parties, including the family, enabling the Sheriff to make factual findings and recommendations concerning Mr. Bayoh's death in a judgment accessible to everyone.

Aamer Anwar, the solicitor representing Mr. Bayoh's family, commented that while the family always anticipated an FAI, they do not currently consider it a full resolution for Sheku Bayoh's death in custody. Anwar described an FAI as essentially the absolute minimum measure, adding that predicting the outcome of the investigations at this point would be premature, especially if they prove genuinely robust and impartial. He highlighted that nearly five months had passed since Sheku's death, and the family's hope was that the Lord Advocate could deliver the truth of what occurred, recognizing that true justice cannot be achieved without it.

A cabinet meeting will discuss findings showing 17 temporary staff are paid over £500 daily, with two earning more than £800. Opposition Conservatives have labelled this spending exorbitant. The Labour-led unitary council defended the outlays, stating specialist expertise was essential for a restructuring program intended to achieve long-term financial savings. Many of these temporary hires, the council explained, provided short-term skills for a project aiming to save £30 million by altering how services are delivered. Conservative councillor Ian Bowyer voiced his concern, stating it seemed Plymouth taxpayers were being asked to take "a tremendous leap in the dark" with an outcome that was "far from clear." The council noted it is hiring permanent staff for five of these roles.

During the extensive Thameslink Programme, engineers have unearthed the forgotten ticket hall and platforms of Southwark Park station. This long-vanished station operated briefly from 1902 until its permanent closure in 1915. The £6.5 billion Thameslink initiative is a major redevelopment effort, rebuilding railway lines that extend from New Cross Gate through London Bridge to Blackfriars and St Pancras.

Perched on a viaduct above Rotherhithe New Road, Southwark Park was among several local stations, including Spa Road, that ceased operations. Their closures were primarily due to increasing competition from trams and buses, exacerbated by the outbreak of World War One.

The discovery occurred as crews constructed the Bermondsey Dive Under. This project involves the partial demolition and reconstruction of two Victorian viaducts, allowing trains from southeast London and Kent to descend beneath a new route intended for Thameslink services from Croydon.

Project manager Greg Thornett explained: "We found the old platform foundations while preparing the viaduct's upper section for new track. Currently, we're working in the former ticket hall's roof area, sealing existing skylights to accommodate the final track alignment." He added that much of the existing viaduct segment will be replaced by the new dive under's access ramps, but the original arch that housed the booking hall will be preserved.

A Thomson Holidays flight successfully delivered hundreds of passengers to the airport, touching down safely around 15:30 BST. The Boeing 737 aircraft promptly taxied to its gate, where ground staff awaited to assist with disembarkation. This smooth arrival was a testament to efficient airport operations, with all passengers, having experienced a comfortable journey, eager to commence their holidays.

Wales international Taylor sustained an injury during Wednesday's training session. Swansea manager Paul Clement is actively pursuing a deal to sign Norwich City's Sweden international, Martin Olsson. Clement emphasized his desire to strengthen the squad, particularly in defensive positions, and believes Olsson would be a valuable asset. The left-back has reportedly travelled to South Wales for a medical examination and discussions, with an agreement potentially finalized before the weekend. Clement, keen to make his mark since taking charge, considers securing Olsson a crucial step in his strategy to avoid Premier League relegation.

A six-year study followed over 200,000 Australians, both smokers and non-smokers aged 45 and older. BMC Medicine reported that the risk of death increased proportionally with cigarette consumption. Daily consumption of 10 cigarettes doubled this risk, and those smoking 20 cigarettes daily faced a four to five times greater likelihood of death. While a smoker might live a long life, their habit significantly reduces this probability. Smoking is known to elevate the risk of numerous health issues, such as heart disease and various cancers.

Cancer Research UK currently estimates that 50% of long-term smokers ultimately succumb to cancer or other diseases linked to smoking. However, more recent data indicates this proportion could be greater. Professor Emily Banks, the lead researcher of the Australian study, noted that newer investigations involving UK women, British physicians, and American Cancer Society volunteers have indicated the figure could be as high as 67%.

Banks commented that while the detrimental effects of smoking were known, their study provided direct, independent evidence corroborating concerning international trends. She added that despite Australia's low smoking rates, their research showed smokers faced approximately three times the risk of premature death compared to non-smokers, and were projected to die about 10 years sooner. George Butterworth, Cancer Research UK's tobacco policy manager, expressed significant worry that the adverse impact of smoking might be more severe than previously understood.

Butterworth noted that previous UK studies conservatively estimated that one in two long-term smokers die from smoking-related conditions, but the new Australian data suggested a higher risk. He cautioned that due to differences in smoking habits between Australia and the UK, such as consumption levels and starting age, the two-in-three figure might not directly translate to the UK population. Currently, around 13% of Australian adults smoke, whereas in the UK, this figure stands at approximately 20%.

Quitting smoking can substantially reduce an individual's health risks. NHS Smokefree states that a decade after cessation, the risk of lung cancer halves compared to continuing smokers, and the risk of heart attack becomes comparable to that of a non-smoker.

A collection featuring photographs, medals, and badges is scheduled for auction later this July. According to auctioneer Charles Hanson, this discovery resembles "a time capsule offering fresh insights into the conflict." The photographs were captured by Robert Oliver, a survivor of the 1899-1902 war. Oliver received the Queen's Medal for South Africa, having participated in battles across Cape Colony, the Orange Free State, and the Transvaal during 1901 and 1902. Mr. Hanson noted that these "graphic images depict the brutal reality and genuine horror of war," a stark contrast to what the Victorian press presented, as the British Empire was then considered invincible. Among the photos are prints showing fallen soldiers in fields, the burial service of a British serviceman, and even a Boer War dog. Furthermore, the collection encompasses two original pairs of kid gloves, spurs, an ammunition bandolier, various caps and hats, a genuine South African feathered headdress, and a cartridge belt. Mr. Hanson revealed that "Robert Oliver was quite the renegade in his younger days. At sixteen, he ran off, boarding a ship for Canada where he took up work as a lumberjack." He subsequently joined the Staffordshire Police force, where he earned a reputation for being "amusing yet resolute and disciplined." Additionally, he owned and operated the Devonshire Pub, located in Hartington, Derbyshire. The auction is set for July 25th.

Between September and November, three incidents involving a single individual have been reported near the Hillhead Halls of Residence. The suspect is described as a white male, aged 17 to 20, approximately 5 ft 8 inches tall, with short dark hair and a slim build. He was consistently observed wearing a dark hooded top and dark trousers during all three occurrences.

The first incident occurred on the evening of Friday, September 15th, when a female student was approached and followed. A second event, on Tuesday, October 3rd, involved a similar approach followed by an attempted theft. The latest incident, on Wednesday, November 8th, escalated to an assault, although the victim did not sustain serious injuries. These events, all transpiring in the immediate vicinity of the Hillhead Halls, have understandably caused significant concern among both residents and staff.

Det. Constable Kirsty Munro, the investigating officer, confirmed that authorities are treating these matters with utmost seriousness and have increased patrols around the Hillhead Halls. She urged anyone with any information, no matter how minor, to come forward, emphasizing that identifying this individual is crucial to preventing further incidents. Residents are advised to remain vigilant and report any suspicious activity immediately to an officer, by calling 101, or anonymously through Crimestoppers.

Early telemetry received after Tuesday's high-speed flyby of the icy dwarf planet (14 km/s or 31,000 mph) confirmed the New Horizons spacecraft remained stable and encountered no problems. This crucial signal was relayed through a large communication antenna located in Madrid, Spain, part of NASA's global network. Traveling across 4.7 billion kilometers of space, the message required four hours and 25 minutes to reach Earth.

Anticipation grew among scientists and engineers at mission control in Laurel, Maryland, as they awaited the vital telemetry. Consequently, immense joy and relief erupted at 01:52 BST when the signal finally arrived, prompting team members to cheer, embrace, and wave American flags in celebration. "We are in lock with telemetry from the spacecraft," announced Alice Bowman, the mission operations manager, upon confirmation of the signal. She added, "We have a healthy spacecraft, we have recorded data from the Pluto system, and we are outbound from Pluto." Minutes later, she conveyed her profound satisfaction, stating, "I can't express how I feel. It's just like we planned it!"

NASA Administrator Charles Bolden remarked that "With this mission, we have visited every single planet in the Solar System," highlighting a significant milestone. John Grunsfeld, the agency's science chief, described the event as "a tremendous moment in human history," further expressing anticipation for the spacecraft's data, which he noted was "full of images and we can't wait."

Alice Bowman, the operations manager, affirmed that New Horizons' solid-state recorder was indeed filled with data. She clarified, "The expected number of segments on that recorder had been used. That tells us that that data has been collected on the spacecraft." The initial signal received Wednesday morning consisted solely of engineering data, intended to verify the successful execution of the flyby sequence. High-resolution images from the encounter were expected to be downlinked later that same day.

Ralph Semmel, director of the Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory, the home of mission control, extended congratulations to the entire mission team. He humorously noted Pluto's offerings: "Whales, doughnuts, and a heart," referring to the informal monikers given to surface features visible in images captured during the spacecraft's approach.

Despite the team's confidence in a successful flyby, there remained a slight risk that New Horizons could be lost while traversing the Pluto system at high speed. A collision with even minute icy debris at its velocity of 14 km/s would have proven fatal to the spacecraft. To mark the occasion, James Christy, discoverer of Pluto's moon Charon, and relatives of Clyde Tombaugh, who discovered the dwarf planet in 1930, gathered at mission control to witness the signal's arrival.

Prime Minister Mrs. May held discussions with Northern Ireland's First and Deputy First Ministers on Monday during a single-day visit to the region. She underscored the commitment to prevent a return to the "borders of the past." Her meeting with Taoiseach Kenny reportedly centered on Brexit's implications for British and Irish relations. Earlier in July, soon after becoming Prime Minister, Mrs. May had a phone conversation with Mr. Kenny, agreeing to strengthen the "strong relationship" between the UK and the Republic of Ireland.

Northern Ireland Secretary of State James Brokenshire characterized Mrs. May's Monday meeting with Arlene Foster and Martin McGuinness as productive. He also stated there was consensus on safeguarding existing border arrangements between Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland. Brokenshire remarked that the Prime Minister had a very constructive discussion with the First and Deputy First Ministers, expressing a strong resolve to avoid the re-establishment of "borders of the past." He noted this theme also underpinned his earlier talks with the Taoiseach last Friday. Mr. Brokenshire further stated that existing "treaties and various other mechanisms" affirm a "distinct arrangement" between the United Kingdom and the Republic of Ireland.

Deputy First Minister Martin McGuinness expressed hope for a future arrangement that enables Northern Ireland residents to retain their European outlook as part of an innovative solution. DUP MP Gavin Robinson identified "two aspects" requiring consideration regarding the border situation. He explained that while talks have primarily addressed human mobility, future conversations must encompass trade, customs procedures, the potential for a single market, and any tariff differences, along with how such disparities would be managed. Robinson noted that while he foresaw no issues in establishing an arrangement based on the Common Travel Area, permitting free movement between the Republic of Ireland and the UK given their consistent immigration policies, he acknowledged that additional talks would likely be necessary.

An armed robbery at the Freshway General store in Southport on Tuesday evening around 9pm BST left a staff member with a facial injury and deeply shaken. Merseyside Police are appealing for witnesses following this incident. Detective Inspector Steve Reardon described it as a "shocking and violent attack" on a lone employee. He confirmed that multiple lines of enquiry are being pursued and urged anyone in the area who saw anything suspicious or has relevant dashcam footage to come forward immediately, stressing that even seemingly insignificant information could be crucial. Police patrols have been increased to reassure local residents.

A man and a woman were forcibly removed from their car by a group of men along a highway between Noida, a Delhi suburb, and Kanpur city on Friday, according to reports. Three male relatives accompanying them were assaulted and tied up. The incident has sparked widespread national outrage and raised concerns about police efficiency.

Some victims alleged they received no response from the official helpline number. One male victim informed the Hindustan Times newspaper that the line was continually busy, and when they finally connected, the officer "repeatedly asked questions instead of rescuing the family." Family members also claimed that a police van drove past the field in Bulandshahr where the incident occurred but did not stop.

On Monday, senior police officer Sujeet Pandey told BBC Hindi that three men, arrested on Sunday, were remanded in prison after being identified by their victims. He added that three more men were detained today. The Uttar Pradesh state government has suspended seven police officers in connection with the incident and established a 300-member taskforce to investigate. The family was also robbed of money, jewellery, and their mobile phones.

Scrutiny of sexual violence in India has increased since the 2012 gang rape and murder of a student on a Delhi bus. Nevertheless, brutal sexual attacks against women and children continue to be reported nationwide.

As of 18 January 2016, 19:54 GMT, VPN services significantly enhance online privacy and security. BBC Technology correspondent Chris Foxx explains their benefits for users in an era of increasing digital surveillance, particularly during this January period.

Celebrated annually on March 8th with parades, speeches, and special events, this day emphasizes gender equality. A query asked readers about their inspiring women and reasons. The discussion page is now closed, with thanks for all comments. Sophie, 11, Oxfordshire, is inspired by Rebecca Adlington to become a swimmer. Iona, 9, Northumberland, chose Charlotte Dujardin for her OBE. Nea named her mum and nan.

The memorial spire is an integral part of the International Bomber Command Centre, established to commemorate the over 55,000 personnel who perished during the conflict. Officials reported that while the damage was superficial, it represented a profound lack of respect. It is believed that the vandals utilized breeze blocks from the site itself in an attempt to scale the inside of the monument.

Nicky Barr, the centre's director, observed that the perpetrators had likely cut through a perimeter fence, with scuff marks inside the memorial probably caused by the falling blocks. She expressed immense disappointment, stating, "It is hugely disappointing that a memorial this county has worked so hard for, that honours the dead of Bomber Command, has been subjected to this kind of abject vandalism." She also conveyed the immense pride felt for the spire, which locals affectionately call 'our memorial', highlighting the significant effort invested despite its recent construction just a year ago. Barr reiterated the act as a clear sign of disrespect. Furthermore, she warned that anyone attempting to climb the approximately 30-meter high structure, with its paved base, would be putting themselves "at real risk of injury," potentially leading to severe harm and being left stranded.

The spire was officially unveiled in October, with approximately 300 Bomber Command veterans in attendance. During World War Two, 125,000 aircrew served in Bomber Command, undertaking 364,514 operational sorties. Of these, a tragic 55,573 aircrew lost their lives, including 25,611 originating from Lincolnshire. Overall, 70% of aircrew were either killed, taken prisoner, or injured.

Last updated 16 November 2016, 14:02 GMT. On its streets, a new generation of photographers offers unique perspectives of the bustling megacity. Adeola Olagunju, 29, is a standout, having shared her approach to capturing Lagos with the BBC. Video Journalist: Roderick Macleod.

On Friday at approximately 8:05 PM, violent attacks occurred in Castlemilk, Glasgow. Police reported that a boy was seriously assaulted while walking in Ardencraig Quadrant, close to its intersection with Ardencraig Drive. His 52-year-old father, who witnessed the incident, was also attacked when he tried to intervene. Both father and son sustained facial injuries and were treated in hospital before being discharged. The two assailants were described as white males, aged between 17 and 21, and wearing dark clothing. Detective Constable Peter McFarlane stated these were "violent and unprovoked" attacks, and officers are conducting door-to-door inquiries and reviewing surveillance footage to identify those responsible. Despite believing the incident was random, additional patrols will be deployed to reassure the public.

In a separate incident, a 23-year-old man was assaulted in Partick around 8:00 PM on Saturday, in what police suspect was a targeted attack. The victim was walking along Exeter Drive, near its junction with Dumbarton Road, when a man exited a passing grey BMW 3 Series saloon, seriously attacked him, then re-entered the car and drove away. Bystanders assisted the injured man, who was hospitalized for head and facial injuries before being released. Police did not provide a description of the suspect but noted his vehicle. Detective Constable David Hardie confirmed they believe this was a targeted assault, with officers currently investigating the area and checking CCTV to gather more information on the circumstances and the perpetrator. Detectives are appealing for anyone with details regarding either assault to come forward.

Queried about potential legal amendments to marriage laws during an ongoing review, he told the BBC's Sunday Politics show he was neither aware of nor intended to implement any such changes. He mentioned the government was exploring humanist marriages in England and Wales. Humanism is a secular philosophy, and while humanist weddings are legally recognized in Scotland, they currently lack legal standing in England, Wales, and Northern Ireland. The Daily Mail reported on Tuesday that ministers had ordered a re-evaluation of wedding legislation, which might permit naturists to officiate weddings. It alleged that Mr. Grayling had issued a paper confirming that groups expressing interest in modifying wedding laws included British Naturism, an organisation promoting understanding and acceptance of outdoor nudism. However, Mr. Grayling clarified to the BBC: "It hasn't been ordered by me, I can tell you that." The justice secretary stressed the difference between someone merely "expressing an interest" and "something actually happening." He stated, "No nude marriage right now, as far as I'm concerned."

Campus streets will be pedestrianized, with additional trees, plants, public art, and cycle routes introduced. A University spokesperson noted the initiative aims to make the campus more inviting, secure, and environmentally friendly for all users.

Jointly funded by the Sheffield City Region Investment Fund and the University, the project is scheduled for completion by September, coinciding with the new academic year. Improvements will encompass public courtyards around the Arts Tower and Western Bank concourse, alongside the creation of a new public park near Broad Lane. Furthermore, additional pedestrian and cycle crossings will be established, and existing ones upgraded.

Keith Lilley, director of estates and facilities management, commented that the development would "transform the campus environment and support the University's links with the city centre." He expressed a desire for Sheffield residents to actively use the campus, whether for dining at its cafes, cycling through to Weston Park, or simply enjoying the newly created greener, safer spaces.

The University is providing £5.1 million for the work, complemented by £2.9 million from the Sheffield City Region Investment Fund. Leigh Bramall of Sheffield City Council highlighted that universities are "critical to the future of Sheffield and vital to the successful economic growth of the city." He further indicated that the improved campus would "emphasize the University's position as a key driver in the local economy."

A 30-year-old Larkhall resident, Paul Newall, tragically lost his life following a collision involving his Kawasaki motorcycle and a white Mazda 2 on the M74 northbound, specifically near junction 7, not far from Hamilton. The fatal incident took place around 1:30 PM on Saturday afternoon, triggering a large emergency services deployment. Despite the swift arrival of paramedics and police, Mr. Newall, known as a popular figure in the Larkhall community, was declared deceased at the site. The carriageway remained shut for several hours to facilitate a thorough accident investigation. Police Scotland is now appealing for witnesses or individuals with dashcam footage to contact them, as they investigate the circumstances of the deadly collision.

Zee Entertainment Enterprises has revealed its intention to dub its extensive collection of Bollywood films, originally recorded in Hindi, into Spanish. This endeavor forms the foundation of Zee Mundo, the company's pioneering effort to introduce Indian cinema to the Hispanic market. The strategic initiative aims to connect with the rapidly expanding Spanish-speaking demographic across the Americas, especially in vital regions like Mexico and the United States. Despite Bollywood's global appeal, language barriers have frequently hindered its widespread reach in areas where Hindi or English are not primary languages. By converting the Hindi dialogue into Spanish, Zee seeks to eliminate this obstacle, making the vibrant storytelling, intricate musical performances, and compelling plots more readily available to a new audience segment. Zee Mundo will feature a varied selection of genres, from action and romance to drama, all customized to local cultural preferences, thereby guaranteeing a diverse viewing experience for its Hispanic audience. This significant expansion highlights Zee Entertainment Enterprises' dedication to enhancing its global presence and securing a strong foothold in a previously untapped market.

The captain scored after Peter Jehle, Vaduz's goalkeeper, fumbled Kieran Smith's shot. Vaduz had established a 2-0 lead by halftime, following quick goals from Gonzalo Zarate and Maurice Brunner. Stuart Jones missed a golden opportunity for Bala to equalize late on, heading wide after Nathan Burke's free-kick found him unmarked at the back post. The decisive return leg will be held at Vaduz's Rheinpark Stadion on Thursday, July 6th. The winners will then face either Ballymena United or Norwegian side Odd in the second qualifying round.

Bala manager Colin Caton shared his thoughts with BBC Wales Sport: "I don't think we began the game particularly well; we were quite sluggish and overly cautious about knowing our opponents. Nevertheless, we still created good opportunities, including a clear penalty when Kieran [Smith] was pulled back after breaking through. Vaduz capitalized on their two first-half chances, which highlights the fine margins at this level. It's genuinely frustrating, as we had the better chances. If we can secure the first goal in the away leg, it's an away goal, and that will put them in a sticky situation. They seemed to be panicking towards the end here. It simply frustrates me that we performed so well, but at this level, you absolutely have to take your opportunities."

A teenager faces charges for drug distribution in East Calder, where authorities are investigating the death of 15-year-old Dione Melville. Emergency services responded to a residence in the town on Sunday morning, but tragically, Dione was pronounced deceased a short while later. Investigators currently classify the death as "unexplained." As a precautionary measure, two other 15-year-old girls were transported to St John's Hospital in Livingston.

Dione was a student at West Calder High School. Acting head teacher Lisa Grubb stated that Dione was a popular girl, and this period is understandably distressing for her loved ones and friends. Ms. Grubb added that Dione was an ambitious young woman with aspirations of pursuing a career in hairdressing and the beauty sector upon graduating this summer. She was highly focused on her future, and the entire school community extends its deepest sympathies to Dione's family and friends during this profoundly sorrowful period.

Many tributes have appeared on social media, posted by her friends. One such message read: "Rest in paradise, my beautiful girl. You didn't deserve to be taken from us. Shine bright, fly high and sleep tight babe. I love and miss you forever and ever my girl."

The Princess Royal Barracks at Deepcut in Surrey became the site of profound tragedy between 1995 and 2002, with four young soldiers dying from gunshot wounds. One of these was Private Sean Benton, a 20-year-old found dead with five gunshot wounds in June 1995 while on guard duty at a perimeter fence. The others who tragically lost their lives were Private Cheryl James, Private Geoff Gray, Private James Collinson, and Private Kevin Williams. Initially, all four deaths were officially classified as suicides, a determination fiercely and persistently challenged by their bereaved families for many years. These families tirelessly campaigned, steadfastly asserting that the circumstances surrounding their children's deaths were deeply suspicious and that the original investigations conducted were fundamentally flawed and inadequate. A significant breakthrough occurred in 2016 when a second inquest into Private Cheryl James’s death, also from Deepcut in 1995, dramatically overturned the initial finding, concluding instead that she was a victim of 'unlawful killing' rather than suicide. Inspired by this landmark ruling, Private Benton’s family, supported by human rights organization Liberty, has now secured consent from the Attorney General to formally apply to the High Court for a fresh inquest into his case.

These Deepcut fatalities soon escalated into a major national scandal, casting a harsh spotlight on the welfare provisions, widespread allegations of bullying, and the overall duty of care exercised within the British Army. The distressed families, frequently aided by human rights groups such as Liberty, relentlessly pursued the quashing of the original inquest verdicts and the initiation of new, impartial inquiries, convinced that vital evidence had either been overlooked or mishandled during the initial processes. Private Cheryl James’s case, in particular, gained renewed prominence when her parents, Des and Doreen James, succeeded in obtaining a fresh inquest after enduring years of arduous legal battles. This subsequent inquest heard compelling and disturbing evidence of a pervasive culture of fear, harassment, and even alleged sexual exploitation present at the barracks, which her family powerfully argued had directly contributed to her tragic demise.

In a parallel development, the family of Private Sean Benton, who was also discovered dead at the same Deepcut Barracks in Surrey, has for an extended period actively sought a new inquest into his death. His sister, Tracy Lewis, along with other family members, has consistently disputed the original suicide verdict, citing numerous inconsistencies and gaps in the available evidence, coupled with a worrying lack of proper investigation at the time of his death. The recent granting of consent by the Attorney General for Private Benton’s family to petition the High Court for a fresh inquest crucially underscores the profound and ongoing concerns about the integrity and thoroughness of the original inquiries conducted into these deeply tragic losses of life.

These pivotal and far-reaching cases, driven by the extraordinary persistence and unwavering courage of the bereaved families and their dedicated legal teams, have had a truly profound and lasting impact on the national understanding of military deaths and the standards of investigation within the armed forces. They have critically and emphatically highlighted the urgent need for independent oversight and a transparent, accountable justice process when service personnel die in non-combat circumstances. The ongoing re-examination of these deeply troubling incidents, particularly through High Court proceedings and the subsequent new inquests, represents a crucial and transformative moment in the collective quest for truth and accountability, offering a significant glimmer of hope for long-awaited closure to families who have endured decades of anguish, uncertainty, and unanswered questions regarding the deaths of their loved ones at Deepcut and similar military establishments.

In 2014, James Percival, aged 66, stated he performed mouth-to-mouth resuscitation on the newborn Jonathan Percival at the vicarage in Freckleton, Lancashire. However, Ruth Percival, 30, contested this, asserting she observed no attempts by him to revive the infant. The inquest was initially suspended in October when new medical findings prompted the coroner to refer the matter to legal authorities. By March, the Crown Prosecution Service concluded there was "insufficient evidence to pursue a prosecution against anyone in connection with Jonathan's death." This decision allowed Coroner Dr. James Adeley to reconvene the inquiry into the circumstances surrounding the child's passing. The hearing, which had begun the previous October, aims to establish the medical cause of death for Jonathan Percival, who was merely 36 hours old when he died at the Freckleton vicarage.

Earlier sessions revealed unsettling details, particularly the markedly different accounts provided by James and Ruth Percival. James Percival, who claimed to have delivered the baby, maintained he attempted to resuscitate the infant through mouth-to-mouth and chest compressions. He described the baby as being born "blue" and not breathing, which necessitated his immediate intervention. Conversely, Ruth Percival, the child's mother, presented a vastly different narrative. She testified that she was in the room throughout the crucial period and did not witness James Percival making any efforts to revive Jonathan, thereby casting significant doubt on his version of events.

The new medical evidence that prompted the coroner to involve prosecutors was not publicly disclosed, but it was understood to have raised specific questions concerning Jonathan's death and the care he received. Despite this, the CPS determined that the evidential threshold for criminal charges could not be met. Jonathan Percival's family, including Ruth Percival, continues to express a strong desire for a complete understanding of what happened to the newborn. The resumed inquest is expected to hear additional expert medical testimony and re-examine the conflicting statements from James and Ruth Percival. The coroner's ultimate goal is to provide a definitive conclusion on the cause and circumstances of Jonathan's tragic death in Freckleton, Lancashire. These ongoing legal proceedings continue to highlight the complexities and emotional toll of the case for all involved, particularly for the parents seeking answers.

The National Environment Research Council (NERC) faced scrutiny for its decision to conduct a public poll to name its new polar research vessel, a contest overwhelmingly won by "Boaty McBoatface." Professor Duncan Wingham, from the NERC, acknowledged the controversy had "put a smile" on people's faces. However, some Members of Parliament, disturbed by the public's mirth and potential ridicule, questioned whether ministers would hold him accountable for the situation. Despite the clear outcome of the poll, the NERC ultimately chose not to name its new £200 million vessel RRS Boaty McBoatface. Instead, it was designated RRS Sir David Attenborough, a choice intended to emphasize its serious scientific mission and critical role in understanding global environmental changes. This rejection of the public's preferred name sparked widespread anger and accusations that the NERC had disregarded democratic will, leading to significant social media uproar over perceived hypocrisy. Prof Wingham, facing intense scrutiny, defended the NERC's decision, arguing that a more dignified name was essential for a vessel undertaking vital polar and climate research. To appease public dissatisfaction, NERC announced a compromise: a remotely operated underwater vehicle (ROV) aboard the RRS Sir David Attenborough would be named 'Boaty McBoatface'. This ingenious solution allowed the beloved, quirky name to be integrated into the scientific mission, ensuring its unique legacy persisted. The entire saga became a memorable case study in public engagement, inextricably linking Professor Wingham and the National Environment Research Council with the Boaty McBoatface phenomenon.

Toulon's coach, Richard Cockerill, reportedly tried to negotiate Leigh Halfpenny's release for the Top 14 final on June 4, assuming his French club reached the showpiece event. Yet, Lions head coach Warren Gatland quickly rejected this proposition, asserting that the schedule was fixed. Gatland firmly stated that Halfpenny would be with the British & Irish Lions training camp for its entirety, stressing that the itinerary was clear and all players must be available from the very beginning. This unwavering position highlights Gatland's absolute dedication to player availability for the crucial tour preparations, deeming it non-negotiable for team unity and strategic development. The Lions squad, including prominent figures like Halfpenny, is set to gather for their pre-tour camp on May 22, just under two weeks prior to the potential Top 14 final. Gatland considers every moment of preparation invaluable, particularly with a rigorous ten-match itinerary, featuring three Tests against the reigning world champions, New Zealand.

Gatland has consistently underscored that the Lions tour's sanctity is paramount, demanding that all chosen players demonstrate full commitment and presence throughout the preparatory phase. This principle has been unequivocally established since the selection process began. The coaching staff is convinced that any early absences would seriously hinder the team's ability to coalesce and achieve the high-calibre performance necessary to contend with the All Blacks on their home ground. Halfpenny, celebrated for his formidable defence, precise goal-kicking, and potent counter-attacks, is deemed an indispensable part of Gatland's strategy. His history with past Lions tours, notably the triumphant 2013 series in Australia, makes his prompt integration into the current squad even more crucial. While Richard Cockerill's efforts to secure Leigh Halfpenny’s availability for such a key club match are understandable from Toulon's point of view, Gatland's steadfast rejection highlights the distinct significance and exacting requirements of the British & Irish Lions tour, which transcends typical club-versus-country rivalries. Attention is now firmly fixed on readying Leigh and his teammates for the immense challenge awaiting them in New Zealand.

Mohammed Abdurezek, with connections to Swansea and Newcastle, was discovered by a dog-walker in Siston, South Gloucestershire, suffering from several stab wounds. An autopsy concluded the 31-year-old's death resulted from multiple stab wounds. Three men, aged 42 and two 22, remain in police custody, an Avon and Somerset Police spokesperson confirmed.

Two charities, Mencap and the Challenging Behaviour Foundation, have highlighted the dangers associated with relocating patients great distances from their homes. This caution coincides with the imminent release of findings from a serious case review concerning patient abuse at a private facility located close to Bristol. The BBC Panorama programme brought this abuse to light through covert filming. Eleven individuals have pleaded guilty to charges of neglect and mistreatment linked to the incidents. The South Gloucestershire Safeguarding Adults Board (SAB) commissioned an independent expert to conduct this review.

Since the Panorama broadcast in May of the previous year, Mencap and the Challenging Behaviour Foundation have received 260 reports from families detailing abuse and neglect within institutional care settings. Their collaborative report, titled 'Out of Sight', documented numerous severe incidents reported by families, encompassing physical and sexual assault, along with excessive use of restraint.

Mark Goldring, Mencap's chief executive, expressed concern, stating that without a robust government plan to shut down large care facilities and establish suitable local services for individuals with learning disabilities, another scandal akin to Winterbourne View is highly probable. The charities indicated that hundreds of people with learning disabilities are presently housed in assessment and treatment units similar to Winterbourne View. They highlighted that many of these facilities are situated far from patients' homes, increasing their vulnerability to neglect and abuse.

Vivien Cooper, who founded the Challenging Behaviour Foundation, voiced profound worries regarding patient safety and well-being. She elaborated that "hundreds of individuals with learning disabilities are being placed in distant care institutions, often for years unnecessarily, leaving them susceptible to neglect and abuse."

A spokesperson for the Department of Health affirmed their stance: individuals should, whenever feasible, receive support to reside in their own homes within their local communities. While acknowledging that a limited number of cases may necessitate high-quality assessment and treatment services, potentially involving brief inpatient stays, they stressed that this should not replace excellent community-based care. The spokesperson underlined the critical importance of properly commissioning and regularly reviewing all services, ensuring they are not employed as permanent solutions.

Subsequent to the BBC investigation, twenty-four patients were moved from the Castlebeck-operated Winterbourne View hospital, located near Hambrook. The facility closed the subsequent month. The criminal charges specifically pertained to five patients from the hospital, and all those charged are currently awaiting their sentences.

Despite achieving the Olympic qualifying standard six times and finishing third in the trials, the 26-year-old athlete was controversially omitted. Her public statement on eightlane.org revealed her despair: "I accept I will never win an Olympic medal." UK Athletics maintained its standard refusal to comment on individual selection decisions, a stance frequently frustrating for athletes vying for Olympic places. The athlete in question was Shelayna Oskan-Clarke, whose exclusion from the initial women's 800m squad sparked extensive discussion in the athletics community. Even with her consistent high performance and multiple achievements of the stringent qualifying benchmark, Oskan-Clarke's third-place finish at the national trials didn't guarantee her a spot. This was due to UK Athletics' selection policy, which permits discretionary picks for berths not automatically filled by the top two competitors. This contentious approach meant that while strong contender Lynsey Sharp secured her place, the final spot remained a major point of contention. Oskan-Clarke’s powerful declaration on eightlane.org emphasized the profound psychological toll that such uncertainty and perceived injustice can impose on athletes dedicating their lives to their sport. Her public lament resonated widely, as many felt the selection process lacked transparency and fairness, especially given her proven ability to perform at the highest level. The incident highlighted persistent concerns about the subjective nature of certain selection criteria, which can leave athletes feeling vulnerable and disempowered, their Olympic aspirations often hinging on seemingly inexplicable decisions. While UK Athletics upholds its right to select the strongest possible team, the lack of detailed explanations for controversial omissions continues to cause tension between the governing body and its athletes.

Hawick launched the Borders' common riding season on Friday with the appearance of horses. The 2017 Cornet, Ali George, and his Lass, Katy Moffat, guided the procession through the town. Hawick is one of several Borders communities that host these annual summer celebrations. A key part of the ceremony involves a horseback group circling the town's historic boundaries.

Portland's Fancy's Farm is gathering unwanted trees to feed its enthusiastic goats. Farm manager Sue Illsley, who is leading this drive, highlights that these trees offer vital enrichment and a crucial dietary boost for the animals, especially during colder periods. It's an eco-friendly way to repurpose your old Christmas tree and support the farm's cherished goats.

The Met Office issued a yellow 'be aware' warning at 08:45, alerting the Highlands, parts of Aberdeenshire, and central Scotland to impending hazardous conditions. This warning details ice and snow accumulation of approximately 4 cm (one inch) on the ground, expected to persist throughout the day, particularly impacting higher elevations and untreated surfaces. Officials advise that these weather conditions are likely to create difficult driving situations across numerous routes in Aberdeenshire, central Scotland, and the Highlands. Motorists are urged to exercise extreme caution, allocate extra time for their journeys, and carefully consider the necessity of their travel. Specific concerns have been raised for major thoroughfares such as the A9, A90, and A82, where strong winds could exacerbate the situation by causing drifting snow and severely reducing visibility, making conditions treacherous. Public transport operators, including bus and rail services, may also experience delays or cancellations as a direct result of the challenging weather. While local authorities in Scotland are working to ensure priority roads are gritted, secondary and rural routes are expected to bear the brunt of the conditions. The yellow warning is anticipated to remain active until at least midnight on Friday, with the Met Office promising further updates as the situation evolves. Residents in the affected regions are advised to regularly check local news and weather reports for the latest information and to prepare for potential disruptions to their daily activities. Already, schools in some remote areas of Aberdeenshire have declared closures or delayed openings. The general advice includes dressing in warm layers, carrying emergency provisions in vehicles, and avoiding non-essential travel, particularly during peak snowfall. The combined threat of falling snow, freezing rain, and high winds presents a considerable hazard for both drivers and pedestrians across Scotland, emphasizing the critical need for vigilance on all journeys.

Following Wednesday's attack, Afghanistan's intelligence service attributed responsibility to militants purportedly supported by Islamabad. In response, the Afghanistan Cricket Board (ACB) issued a declaration stating its unwillingness to compete against "a country where terrorists are housed and provided safe havens." This unprecedented move by the ACB to suspend cricket relations highlights growing diplomatic friction between Kabul and Islamabad, potentially jeopardizing a scheduled T20 series and future bilateral sporting events. The Pakistan Cricket Board (PCB) swiftly countered, criticizing the ACB for "playing politics" and expressing regret over the entanglement of sports in political disputes. A PCB representative reportedly stressed cricket's unifying nature, asserting that "Cricket should unite people, not divide them."

The PCB also drew attention to its long-standing commitment to developing Afghan cricketing talent, noting that numerous Afghan players have gained vital experience through Pakistan's domestic competitions and the Pakistan Super League (PSL). This sporting connection, forged over years of shared enthusiasm, now seems profoundly compromised. Conversely, Afghanistan's view is that its intelligence agencies' direct connection of the recent assault to alleged elements based in Pakistan renders typical sporting interactions impossible. The ACB's stance mirrors a widespread national demand for accountability and a halt to what Kabul perceives as cross-border terrorism. The Afghan government has repeatedly accused Islamabad of backing militant organizations that destabilize Afghanistan, an allegation Pakistan strenuously refutes, maintaining it faces similar terrorism threats originating from its border regions.

This deadlock presents a substantial obstacle for the future of cricketing relations between the two countries. The diplomatic repercussions of the incident are thus severely impacting the likelihood of swift reconciliation, extending beyond politics into the realm of sports. The resolute position of the Afghanistan Cricket Board, supported by the Afghan government, indicates that as long as Afghanistan does not observe a concrete change in Islamabad's approach concerning alleged militant sanctuaries, the sporting domain will remain tied to their deep-seated political resentments. While the Pakistan Cricket Board persists in advocating for the decoupling of sports and politics, the continued presence of these fundamental security issues leaves the future of cricket between these fervent competitors highly precarious.

Julian Salvi, the 31-year-old Australian, sustained an injury during the Chiefs' narrow Champions Cup defeat to Ulster and will undergo surgery. Salvi arrived at the Chiefs from Leicester in summer 2015 and quickly established himself as a vital player in the squad that reached the Premiership final last season. Head coach Rob Baxter stated, "While we're still awaiting the full diagnosis, the injury appears to be quite serious." Before joining the Chiefs, Salvi was twice nominated for the Premiership's Player of the Year award during his time at Leicester and previously captained Australia's Under-21 team. "His immense 80-minute contribution is what we'll likely miss most," Baxter conveyed to BBC Sport. Baxter further explained, "His greatest attribute is his reliability. He performs consistently every week; even when the team or individual players have struggled, Julian's performance has consistently been outstanding. He is almost always our leading tackler and breakdown clearer, and what many people underestimate is his significance to our offensive play. While many associate open-side flankers with tackling, defending, and disruption, Julian's extensive breakdown clearing makes him incredibly vital to our attack."

Facing a decline in demand and escalating expenses, the company has "temporarily halted" operations at its Redcar blast furnace. SSI, which took over the previously mothballed Tata Steel site in 2010, employs almost 2,000 individuals there.

According to Ms. Soubry, European Union regulations restrict the government's ability to directly provide financial aid to British steel manufacturers. Cornelius Louwrens, SSI's chief operating officer, pressed the government to "take concrete action, not just offer words," to help ensure the plant's survival. He emphasized that "other nations in Europe are actively supporting their steel sectors because they recognize its critical importance."

He requested ministers to endorse the backing of "essential projects," which would enable SSI to obtain commercial credit, alongside reducing corporate taxes and loosening regulations related to carbon dioxide emissions.

However, Ms. Soubry reiterated that "exceptionally stringent state aid rules, particularly affecting the steel industry, limit our options." She clarified that while "funding for initiatives like research and development is permissible, providing direct loans or underwriting is not." She acknowledged the "extremely challenging circumstances at SSI," but maintained that the government's "hands are tied." Despite this, she stated they "will continue to collaborate with the company and trade unions," identifying global steel overproduction as the fundamental problem. She added that "the Prime Minister views this as a crucial British industry, and the government remains committed to offering all possible support."

Union representatives at the facility called the company's choice "catastrophic" and have requested immediate discussions with management.

Queen's Lodge in Colwyn Bay, originally the residence of the first Lord Colwyn, was converted into two care facilities after the 1946 death of industrialist and banker, Frederick Henry Smith. The estate's extensive grounds boasted a lake, a croquet lawn, a bowling green, and prize-winning gardens. The final sale price remains undisclosed. Records from the National Monuments Record of Wales indicate it was acquired in 1946 by the former Merseyside Hospitals Council, a health insurance program. Individuals from Merseyside utilized the property for recuperation, often sending postcards featuring images of the main house and its surroundings to their families and friends. Queen's Lodge was renamed the John Braddock Convalescent Home, while the Mary Bamber Convalescent Centre was constructed within its premises. The Colwyn Bay Heritage Group highlighted Queen's Lodge as a significant structure, having been the ancestral home of Lord Colwyn and his family, who were renowned as "great benefactors of the town." Agents Legat Owen commented that the entire site presented potential for diverse applications.

Scott Quigg, a former WBA super-bantamweight titleholder, could move significantly closer to a highly anticipated bout against Welshman Lee Selby should he emerge victorious this Saturday. Quigg himself labeled it a "tremendous chance," explaining he has "relentlessly pursued this moment." He acknowledged Selby as a "premier competitor," stating that defeating him would "relaunch his bid for a world title." However, Quigg stressed his "undivided attention remains on Saturday's contest," emphasizing he "must not underestimate his opponent" as "each fight builds towards the next." He affirmed his readiness "for any challenge his adversary presents." Promoter Eddie Hearn has long envisioned a significant domestic clash between Quigg and Selby, confident it would be a major attraction for UK boxing enthusiasts. Hearn noted that "both Scott and Lee possess extraordinary abilities and vast fan bases." He added, "The public desires these high-profile encounters, and should Scott perform well on Saturday, we will certainly be vigorously pursuing that matchup. It's an exciting prospect for Wales and indeed, the entire British boxing scene." Quigg reiterated Hearn's views, asserting his preparedness for such a challenge. He further stated, "I am certain I will secure the win this Saturday. After that, discussions about Lee can truly begin. I seek the most significant fights, and he represents one of those."

Aged 33, the forward's career began at Northampton, followed by spells at Mansfield, Lincoln, and Chester. After netting 10 goals in 39 league games for Shrewsbury, he secured a £50,000 transfer to French club Nice, but moved to Hamilton two years later. He has since played in Bulgaria and most recently in South Korea. Asamoah, set to wear number 25 for Carlisle, has earned four Ghana caps, scoring once.

Campaign group Liberty strongly opposes the Investigatory Powers Act, labelling its provisions an "assault on our freedom" due to their enabling of mass surveillance. This law, enacted in November and nicknamed the 'Snooper's Charter' by critics, empowers agencies like MI5, MI6, and GCHQ with broad surveillance capabilities. Liberty's director, Martha Spurrier, argues the act allows for indiscriminate data gathering on ordinary citizens, creating a perilous precedent for civil liberties rather than focusing on genuine threats. She considers it among the most extreme surveillance legislation in democratic nations.

The Act's powers include collecting vast amounts of data from electronic devices, remotely controlling or modifying them, intercepting communications such as texts, online messages, and emails, monitoring phone calls, and tracking location. It also mandates internet service providers to store users' browsing histories for a year. Despite considerable opposition, including calls from the House of Lords for enhanced privacy safeguards, the government, led by then-Prime Minister Theresa May, successfully passed the bill. May maintained the Act was essential for national security in the digital age, asserting it merely updated existing powers while introducing transparency and oversight via independent judicial commissioners.

However, Liberty and other privacy advocates continue to dispute its proportionality, citing concerns over bulk data collection, device hacking, and the year-long browsing history retention mandates as unacceptable intrusions. Anticipated legal challenges, potentially reaching the European Court of Human Rights, highlight the inherent conflict between state security and individual rights, with critics warning of a chilling effect on free expression.

The 26-year-old, boasting over 160 career appearances, previously featured as a midfielder for SC Amiens, Rayo Vallecano, and Dijon, and can also cover centre-back. MK boss Robbie Neilson told the League One club's website that a reliable French contact recommended the player, whom they'd thoroughly scouted. Neilson expects him to "bring physicality and strength to the middle of the pitch." For all the latest football transfers, visit our dedicated page.

Thomas Groome, then 53, vanished from Thorne in Doncaster on New Year's Day, 2010, the last time his family saw him. His disappearance prompted a substantial three-year investigation by South Yorkshire Police. Despite extensive searches, Mr. Groome's body has never been recovered, a deeply distressing fact that remained central throughout the legal proceedings.

Jason Thaxter, from Hexthorpe, Doncaster, was ultimately convicted of murder and conspiracy to prevent a lawful burial following a five-week trial at Sheffield Crown Court. He received a minimum 17-year prison sentence before being eligible for parole. The trial revealed how Thaxter had brutally killed Mr. Groome and then deliberately taken steps to hide his remains. The absence of a body presented considerable challenges for detectives, yet the prosecution successfully built a compelling case against Thaxter.

During sentencing, Judge Roger Thomas QC characterized Thaxter's actions as "callous and calculated," underscoring the profound and prolonged anguish inflicted upon Mr. Groome's family, who have been denied the opportunity to lay him to rest. South Yorkshire Police commended their team's tenacious efforts in securing a conviction in this complex "no-body" murder case. Mr. Groome's family continues to make heartfelt appeals for any information regarding the location of his remains, yearning to finally bring him home and find some measure of peace.

Profits at the tech titan increased by 17% compared to the same period last year. CEO Steve Ballmer stated that their "devices and services transformation" was progressing well, adding that a "wide range" of new products would be launched in the upcoming quarter. The report, however, offered no new details regarding Ballmer's successor, as he had previously announced plans to retire within the next year.

This quarter, the company released several new offerings, including an update to Windows 8, and recently completed the acquisition of struggling Finnish giant Nokia's mobile phone unit. Bolstered by the strong results, shares climbed 6% in after-hours trading.

Microsoft also disclosed sales figures for its tablet computer, Surface, for the first time. Revenues from Surface reached $400 million, showing sequential growth in both revenue and units sold compared to the previous quarter. This positive news follows a challenging last quarter, where the company incurred an embarrassing $900 million write-down due to sluggish sales of the device. Despite being well-regarded by reviewers and marking Microsoft's initial venture into hardware manufacturing, many consumers, already expressing dissatisfaction with Microsoft's Windows operating system update, did not embrace it. The company still withheld exact sales figures for the device.

Investors hoping for information about Ballmer's replacement in the new year were left disappointed. Earlier today, during an an earnings conference call, Ford CEO Alan Mulally declined to comment on rumors that he was being considered for the top executive role. Other potential candidates include Stephen Elop, former head of Nokia, who resigned after Microsoft announced its September plan to purchase Nokia's mobile phone division for 5.4 billion euros ($7.2 billion; £4.6 billion). Mr. Elop currently leads Devices and Services at Nokia, but is expected to transition to Microsoft, where he previously held a senior management position, once the deal concludes. Ballmer has served as Microsoft's CEO since 2000 and has been with the company since 1980.

Discussions have commenced following a decision by Papua New Guinea's Supreme Court which declared the detention facility unconstitutional, effectively nullifying a prior agreement between the two governments. Australia uses this site as part of its offshore asylum processing policy. Papua New Guinea has now announced its intention to close the facility, though the exact timeline for this remains uncertain.

Opened in 2001, Manus Island has, alongside Australia's other offshore processing centers, played a significant role in Australia's controversial asylum strategy. Charles Lepani, PNG's high commissioner to Australia, asserted that the detainees are now Australia's responsibility, yet Australia has consistently refused to accept any of them. Immigration Minister Peter Dutton stated on Thursday that space was available at another detention center on Nauru. Mr. Dutton confirmed that while capacity exists on Nauru, negotiations are ongoing with the PNG government to explore alternative arrangements within PNG.

This development follows an incident on Wednesday where an Iranian asylum seeker, held at the Australian-funded detention center on Nauru, set himself on fire. The Nauruan government described his actions as a "political protest." Mr. Dutton reported that the 23-year-old man was in a critical condition and had been evacuated to Australia for medical treatment, indicating a poor prognosis. Nauru, a small Pacific island nation, is situated approximately 3,000 km (1,800 miles) northeast of Australia. It was formerly administered by Australia before gaining independence in 1968.

Mr. Dutton clarified that the self-immolation occurred in a settlement outside the detention center. He also confirmed that other asylum seekers on the island had engaged in self-harm. He reiterated Australia's firm policy that individuals transferred to Australia for medical assistance would be returned to Nauru once their treatment was complete. Three people, he noted, had already been returned to Nauru from Australia after receiving the medical care they sought. Representatives from the UN refugee agency UNHCR were reportedly visiting Nauru when the incident took place. Separately, an Iranian asylum seeker was fined last month for a suicide attempt during an attempt to transfer him and his daughter from the Nauru center.

The detailed terms of the agreement indicate a different reality, revealing that GM effectively absorbed a cost of up to £6 billion to divest itself of Vauxhall and Opel. Firstly, a substantial portion of this sum – £750 million – was allocated not for vehicle manufacturing facilities, but to cover loans previously taken out by the owners of Opel and Vauxhall. This unusual arrangement underscores that GM was not merely selling an asset, but was actively paying to relinquish a long-standing financial burden. The majority of the £6 billion charge, however, originates from the significant pension liabilities that GM opted to retain instead of transferring to Peugeot. Estimates suggest GM's continued responsibility for pension obligations for Vauxhall and Opel employees totals well over £5 billion, reflecting the immense expense of legacy commitments accumulated over decades. This decision, made in Detroit, highlights GM's strategic imperative to cleanse its balance sheet of European losses that have hampered its financial performance for years. By holding onto these liabilities, GM avoided the potentially complex and drawn-out negotiations that would have been necessary to offload them to Peugeot, thereby expediting the sale and ensuring a clean separation.

Therefore, this deal represents less a profitable sale for GM and more an expensive departure from a market where it consistently struggled to compete. For Peugeot, the acquisition of Vauxhall and Opel offers a significant opportunity to boost its market share in Europe and achieve considerable economies of scale. However, it also means inheriting a business that has been unprofitable for nearly two decades, demanding substantial restructuring and investment to achieve profitability. Peugeot's key challenge will be to efficiently integrate Vauxhall and Opel's operations, streamline production, and reduce costs without alienating its workforce or diminishing the brands' appeal. Under its new ownership, Vauxhall's focus will be on sharing platforms with Peugeot models, standardizing components, and rationalizing its product portfolio to enhance profitability. This move signals a definitive shift in GM's global strategy, allowing it to concentrate resources on more lucrative markets like North America and China, and to heavily invest in future technologies such as electric and autonomous vehicles. The detachment from Vauxhall and Opel frees up capital and management attention, enabling GM to pursue its growth ambitions elsewhere, even if this strategic freedom came with a hefty £6 billion price tag.

David Craig Ellis, 41, has confessed to killing Alec Warburton, 59, at a house on Lon Masarn in Sketty, Swansea. Emergency services attended the property. Ellis entered a guilty plea for manslaughter at Swansea Crown Court; sentencing was adjourned. The court heard Mr Warburton's death resulted from an altercation.

Mr. Mills had served as deputy chairman for the primary "out" campaign, officially recognized by the Electoral Commission. He had previously alleged that the campaign was plagued by internal disputes. Reports indicated he was close to resigning in February when Labour MP Kate Hoey joined a competing "out" group.

In his letter of resignation, the home shopping executive explained his belief that a robust and independent Labour perspective advocating for leaving the EU would prove more beneficial and effective for the Leave campaign. He noted that he could now fully devote himself to his role as director of Labour Leave, thereby cultivating that distinct voice. He added that, leading up to the 23 June vote, Labour Leave intended to present a powerful and well-reasoned left-of-centre case for Britain's exit from the EU.

The overwhelming majority of Labour Members of Parliament favor Britain remaining within the EU, with only approximately twelve actively campaigning for departure. Former Labour minister Frank Field cautioned the party that its stance on remaining in the EU risked alienating a significant number of voters, potentially losing them to UKIP. Mr. Mills, who played a key role in the 1975 referendum campaign against European Economic Community membership, has also expressed disapproval of Jeremy Corbyn's decision to support staying in.

Mr. Mills voiced his hope that his choice would be a transformative initial step in encouraging Labour supporters, who are still undecided, to vote Leave in June to secure a better, fairer future for the country.
